postcontent: I have decided to sell my HK MR556A1 with Aimpoint PRO. This rifle has a BD date code. For those that don't know, the HK MR556 is a short stroke piston operated rifle built as a civilian version of the 416. The 416 is in use by Marines (IAR27) and by select special forces. It is an outstandingly clean operating system. It also has been upgraded with HK licensed Troy Micro flip-up front and rear sights($190). The sights give absolute 1-1 co-witness to the Aimpoint.  It has had the barrel re-profiled to the SOCOM profile by Jayson at IGF. He re-profiles and works on HK's for a living. His work is second to none. It also comes with a 14.5" SS barrel custom made to fit the HK MR556 and 416, it has been Duracoated and includes a BCM flash hider with pin to lengthen it to 16" overall. I bought the barrel for another upper but decided to let it go. The upper has a zero round count, while the lower has a 30 rounds or less count. I used it with my other upper to test the other uppers accuracy. I have a larger trigger guard on it but includes stock flat trigger guard. It has 7 HK High Reliability Magazines (2 I bought used and 5 never fired). It also has 5 HK polymer magazines. It comes with all the paperwork and hard case from HK. I will include the Vickers Padded Combat two point sling with quick release. The Aimpoint PRO is used but in perfect condition with box,spacer (not used as to give co-witness to the HK low profile sights), and paperwork. There is almost $500 worth of magazines at HK's price. The total of the barrel re-profile and nitriding (meloniting) is $340. The extra barrel (new), I put a value of $300 even though it cost more than that to have it made and include an extra barrel nut (not pictured). I also have an HK barrel nut tool that will fit HK's proprietary barrel nut. On a side note the barrel tab was removed by Jayson to allow either the MR556 or 416 BCGs to fit the upper, the 14.5" barrel was made without the tab, so it will work with either also. I honestly am not looking to trade for anything. Please note that I will drive within a reasonable area to meet, but prefer to deal FTF. Must show ID, CCW or PPP to buy this. Sorry for the inconvenience, but better safe than sorry. Price is firm and not negotiable. postcontent:

Handmade by James B. Lile.  Has sheath. Has case and belt clip.  This isn't a Dot or stamp knife.  It's scripted ' Handmade by James B. Lile '.  Unlike the guys who bought jimmylile website from Jimmy's wife who have nothing to do with jimmy and you can't even get them to tell you who actually made their ' so called ' Jimmy Lile knife,  Jimmy Lile himself made this one.  And unlike those when the romantics for Rambo die down people will want a Knife Jimmy Lile made himself.  Not a Dot knife they don't even know the man that made theirs, try it ask them.     The knives Jimmy himself made.....are very few and far between , and will appreciate in value at incredible rates.   Possibly even fund your retirement if you buy early enough.  
Ronald Reagan had Jimmy visit his Chateau, he had him make him a Folding Lile Knife.  Jimmy gave it to him and The President responded by giving him a Silver Medallion of the 40th presidential seal of the United States.  And giving his wife Marilyn the same in two cuff links. In 1971, Lile became a full-time knifemaker and was known as "Gentleman Lile" or "The Arkansas Knifemaker". He was particularly known for his Survival knife designs known as "The Mission" series, created by request for Sylvester Stallone to use in his first two Rambo movies. These designs would go on to influence other knife makers in the 1980s. In addition to creating the Rambo knives, Lile designed and made several Bowie knives that he presented to Governor Bill Clinton and U.S. Presidents Ronald Reagan, Richard Nixon, and Gerald R. Ford, Jr. Other owners of his work included John Wayne, Peter Fonda, Fess Parker, Bo Derek, and Johnny Cash
And everyone knows Slyvester Stallone had him make the Rambo knife in which he uses In the Rambo Movie.  

President Clinton talks Jimmy Lile

title: For Sale/Trade:  Akdal mka 1919
postcontent: The Akdal MKA 1919 is a gas operated, semi-automatic shotgun that resembles the M16 rifle and mimics the layout and placement of some of the controls. It was created by Turkish company Akdal Arms. The MKA 1919 uses a conventional gas-operated action which is located around the support tube that runs below the barrel. The return spring is also located around the same support tube which is concealed by an enlarged polymer handguard. The MKA 1919 barrel can be quickly removed from upper receiver. To charge the rifle, the charging handle on the receiver must be pulled. The upper receiver is manufactured from an aluminum alloy while the lower receiver, along with pistol grip and shoulder stock, is manufactured as one piece from impact-resistant polymer. Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic rifle has a 5 round detachable box magazine. It has a bolt release identical in location and function to the one on the M16. Manual safety also duplicates M16-style being located on the left side of the receiver above the pistol grip.[1] Standard sights include a front post installed on the M16-style removable base and a detachable M16A2-style carrying handle with built-in diopter sight. On the upper receiver, an integral Picatinny rail exists which will accept detachable carrying handle or optional red-dot or other optical sight attachments.
